ng Team VR46]]\n|align=center| 13\n|{{Flagicon|Italy}} [[Celestino Vietti]]<ref name=\"VR46\">{{cite news|url=https://www.motogp.com/en/news/2019/09/19/sky-racing-team-vr46-confirm-moto2-moto3-line-ups/309411|title=SKY Racing Team VR46 confirm Moto2\u2122, Moto3\u2122 line-ups |date=19 September 2019|accessdate=22 September 2019|work=MotoGP.com|publisher=[[Dorna Sports]]}}</ref>\n| 1\n|-\n|align=center| 16\n|{{Flagicon|Italy}} [[Andrea Migno]]<ref name=\"VR46\"/>\n| 1\n|}\n|valign=\"top\"|\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 85%;\"\n|-\n!colspan=2|Key\n|-\n| Regular rider\n|- style=\"background:#ccffcc;\"\n| Wildcard rider\n|- style=\"background:#ffcccc;\"\n| {{nowrap|Replacement rider}}\n|}\n|}\n\n* All teams use series-specified [[Dunlop tyres]].\n\n===Team changes===\n* [[Tech3]] joined the Moto3 class after KTM's withdrawal from Moto2.\n* [[Husqvarna Motorcycles|Husqvarna]] returned to Moto3 after a four-year absence with [[Max Biaggi|Sterilgarda Max Racing Team]].<ref name=\"Husky\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.husqvarna-motorcycles.com/gb/news/int/husky-moto3-announcement/|title=HUSQVARNA MOTORCYCLES SET TO RETURN TO MOTO3 WORLD CHAMPIONSHIP|date=11 August 2019|accessdate=1 November 2019|work=husqvarna-motorcycles.com|publisher=[[Husqvarna Motorcycles]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.motogp.com/en/in%20the%20media/2019/11/06/first-look-2020-husqvarna-moto3-machine/317473|title=First look: 2020 Husqvarna Moto3\u2122 machine|date=6 November 2019|accessdate=11 November 2019|work=MotoGP.com|publisher=[[Dorna Sports]]}}</ref>\n* WorldwideRace Team shut down after twenty-two seasons.\n* [[Max Biaggi|Sterilgarda Max Racing Team]] and [[Ajo Motorsport|Red Bull KTM Ajo]] both expanded to two riders.\n* Angel Nieto Team reverted to their former name of Aspar.<ref name=\"crash.net\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.crash.net/motogp/news/934734/1/angel-nieto-team-reverts-aspar-team-name-2020|title=Angel Nieto Team reverts to Aspar Team name from 2020|author=Cobb, Haydn|date=29 November 2019|accessdate=24 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Rider changes===\n* Leopard Racing ran 2 different riders from the previous season - [[Jaume Masi\u00e1]], who joins from the WorldwideRace team, and [[Dennis Foggia]], who joins from [[Sky Racing Team by VR46|Sky Racing Team VR46]]. They replaced [[Lorenzo Dalla Porta]] and [[Marcos Ram\u00edrez (motorcyclist)|Marcos Ram\u00edrez]], who moved up to Moto2 with Italtrans Racing Team and American Racing respectively.\n* [[Ar\u00f3n Canet]] moved up to Moto2 with [[\u00c1ngel Nieto Team|Gaviota \u00c1ngel Nieto Team]]. He was replaced at [[Max Biaggi|Sterilgarda Max Racing Team]] by [[Alonso L\u00f3pez (motorcyclist)|Alonso L\u00f3pez]], who joins from [[Emilio Alzamora|Estrella Galicia 0,0]].\n* [[Filip Sala\u010d]] left Pr\u00fcstelGP to join VNE Snipers, replacing [[Romano Fenati]], who joins [[Max Biaggi|Sterilgarda Max Racing Team]].\n* [[Jakub Kornfeil]] was originally intended to leave Pr\u00fcstelGP to join [[Aleix Espargar\u00f3|BOE Skull Rider Mugen Race]]. However, in January 2020, Kornfeil announced his retirement from professional racing. His seat was taken by [[Davide Pizzoli]], who made his full season debut in Moto3.\n* [[Jason Dupasquier]] and [[Barry Baltus]] made their debut with Pr\u00fcstelGP.\n* [[Andrea Migno]] returned to [[Sky Racing Team by VR46|Sky Racing Team VR46]] after two seasons.\n* [[Maximilian Kofler]] made his full season debut in Moto3, joining CIP Green Power. He became the first Austrian rider to compete as a regular rider since [[Michael Ranseder]] in the 2009 season.\n* [[2019 Red Bull MotoGP Rookies Cup]] winner [[Carlos Tatay]] made his full season debut with [[Avintia Racing|Reale Avintia Racing]].\n* [[Khairul Idham Pawi]] returned to Moto3 by joining [[SIC Racing Team|Petronas Sprinta Racing]]. He replaced [[Ayumu Sasaki]], who joins [[Tech 3|Red Bull KTM Tech 3]].\n* [[Yuki Kunii]] signed for [[Hiroshi Aoyama|Honda Team Asia]] to replace [[Kaito Toba]] who joined [[Ajo Motorsport|Red Bull KTM Ajo]] next season.\n* [[Ra\u00fal Fern\u00e1ndez (motorcyclist)|Ra\u00fal Fern\u00e1ndez]] joined [[Ajo Motorsport|Red Bull KTM Ajo]] to replace [[Can \u00d6nc\u00fc]] who moved to the [[2020 Supersport World Championship|Supersport World Championship]].\n* [[Deniz \u00d6nc\u00fc]] made his full season debut with [[Tech 3|Red Bull KTM Tech 3]].\n* [[Riccardo Rossi (motorcyclist)|Riccardo Rossi]] left Gresini Team to join BOE Skull Rider Mugen Race, replacing [[Makar Yurchenko]] whose contract was terminated.\n\n===Mid season changes===\n* [[Dirk Geiger]] will replace [[Barry Baltus]] for the first 3 races due to age restriction.\n\n==Calendar==\nThe following Grands Prix are scheduled to take place in 2020:<ref>{{cite news|title=2020 MotoGP calendar confirmed|url=https://www.crash.net/motogp/news/935546/1/2020-motogp-calendar-confirmed|date=23 January 2020|accessdate=23 January 2020|work=Crash.net|publisher=CMG}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 85%;\"\n|-\n!Round\n!Date\n![[List of Grand Prix motorcycle races|Grand Prix]]\n![[List of Grand Prix motorcycle circuits|Circuit]]\n|-\n!1\n|8 March\n| {{flagicon|QAT}} [[Qatar motorcycle Grand Prix|QNB Grand Prix of Qatar]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.motogp.com/en/news/2019/03/07/motogp-to-race-at-losail-international-circuit-until-2031/285417|title=MotoGP\u2122 to race at Losail International Circuit until 2031|date=7 March 2019|accessdate=7 March 2019|work=MotoGP.com|publisher=[[Dorna Sports]]}}</ref>\n| [[Losail International Circuit]], [[Lusail]]\n|-\n!2\n|31 May\n| nowrap=\"nowrap\" |{{flagicon|ITA}} [[Italian motorcycle Grand Prix|Gran Premio d'Italia Oakley]]\n| nowrap=\"nowrap\" |[[Mugello Circuit]], [[Scarperia e San Piero]]\n|-\n!3\n|7 June\n| {{flagicon|CAT}} [[Catalan motorcycle Grand Prix|Gran Premi Monster Energy de Catalunya]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.motogp.com/en/news/2016/11/09/circuit-de-barcelona-catalunya-to-host-motogp-until-2021/215496|title=Circuit de Barcelona-Catalunya to host MotoGP\u2122 until 2021|date=9 November 2016|accessdate=9 November 2016|work=MotoGP.com|publisher=[[Dorna Sports]]}}</ref>\n| [[Circuit de Barcelona-Catalunya]], [[Montmel\u00f3]]\n|-\n!4\n|21 June\n| {{flagicon|DEU}} [[German motorcycle Grand Prix|HJC Helmets Motorrad Grand Prix Deutschland]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Future of German Motorcycle Grand Prix secured|url=http://www.motogp.com/en/news/2016/07/17/future-of-german-motorcycle-grand-prix-secured/205773|date=17 July 2016|accessdate=17 July 2016|work=MotoGP.com|publisher=[[Dorna Sports]]}}</ref>\n| [[Sachsenring]], [[Hohenstein-Ernstthal]]\n|-\n!5\n|28 June\n| {{flagicon|NLD}} [[Dutch TT|Motul TT Assen]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.motogp.com/en/news/2016/06/25/ten-more-years-in-assen/204268|title=Ten more years in Assen|date=25 June 2016|accessdate=25 June 2016|work=MotoGP.com|publisher=[[Dorna Sports]]}}</ref>\n| [[TT Circuit Assen]], [[Assen]]\n|-\n!6\n|12 July\n| {{flagicon|FIN}} [[Finnish motorcycle Grand Prix|Grand Prix of Finland]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://en.kymiring.fi/|title=MOTOGP WILL BE HELD IN 2020\u20132024 This contract is valid for five years, and the race will be held at KymiRing. Events of the World Championships will come back in Finland after 40 years.|date=3 August 2017|accessdate=3 August 2017|work=Kymiring.|publisher=[[Kymi Ring]]}}</ref>\n| [[Kymi Ring]], [[Iitti]]\n|-\n!7\n|9 August\n| {{flagicon|CZE}} [[Czech Republic motorcycle Grand Prix|Monster Energy Grand Prix \u010cesk\u00e9 republiky]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.motogp.com/en/news/2016/01/12/dorna-extends-contract-with-brno-until-2020/191820|title=Dorna extends contract with Brno until 2020|date=12 January 2016|accessdate=12 January 2016|work=MotoGP.com|publisher=[[Dorna Sports]]}}</ref>\n| [[Automotodrom Brno]], [[Brno]]\n|-\n!8\n|16 August\n| {{flagicon|AUT}} [[Austrian motorcycle Grand Prix|myWorld Motorrad Grand Prix von \u00d6sterreich]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www